7. opimium damnatum etc. ι Cassius had stated that even greater men have been condemned in spite of their services to the state and their influential friends, and blamed Cicero for his exertions on Plancius' behalf ; Cicero shows that their friends did their best for them, and he is prepared to follow their example.

Opimius, consul 121 B.c., was instrumental in suppressing the rising of C. Gracchus, In 120 Rc. he was accused by Didius of having put Roman citizens to death without trial, and in spite of the defence of the consul Papirius Carbo was banished. He died in exile at Dyrrhachium.
